Exploitation


After changing the permission of the SSH key, I successfully gained access to the target machine using the SSH key as simon. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


I have access to the root's home directory. There is an interesting file called read_message.c. This program will provide an output if the name matches Simon. However, I am unable to execute the /usr/local/sbin/message file.


Running LinPeas shows there is another interesting file called read_message located at /usr/local/bin, and I have read & execution permission over it.


Looks like the only way to obtain a root shell is by exploiting the /usr/local/sbin/read_message application. This application has a character buffer of 20 for the input; however, the program only checks if the first five characters are correct. Meaning we can overflow it.


And now I have a root shell by exploiting the buffer to execute the command by appeneding Simon and then fifteen a, so it matches 20 length.
